Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Views Committee Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paper Views Committee Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0605085194 Amman AL-RA'Y in Arabic 6 May 94 pp 1, 27 </F>
<F P=103> JN0605085194 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-RA'Y </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Developing a Fruitful Cooperation Away From </F>
Slogans"] 
  [Text] Amidst the blizzard of the tempestuous political 
events in our region these days, an important event like the 
resumption of the Joint Jordanian-Egyptian Committee meetings 
seems like a peaceful island in a turbulent sea. This picture 
is strengthened by the fact that the meetings are being held in 
Amman away from slogans, fancy promises, and pan-Arab programs. 
Instead, these meetings are discussing and studying economic, 
trade, scientific, and cultural issues, including the 
establishment of joint ventures between the two fraternal 
countries, in an atmosphere of seriousness and close examination 
out of the limelight. 
  In fact, this kind of bilateral Arab cooperation, which 
touches various parts of the economic and trade life, is not 
receiving enough attention by Arab observers. It has always 
been the practice, and our life is governed by practices, to 
hail only political developments, without paying any attention 
to events and developments that affect Arab citizens' daily 
life, despite the fact that any meaningful political changes or 
developments have economic contexts that affect the lives of 
Arab citizens. 
  Within this context, the resumption of the Joint Jordanian- 
Egyptian Committee meetings following a five-year hiatus is 
truly an important development in relations between the two 
fraternal countries and in inter-Arab affairs. Such a 
development will naturally have a political impact resulting in 
further rapprochement, cooperation, and coordination between 
Amman and Cairo. 
  Although these meetings focused their discussion and study 
on 
economic, trade, scientific, and cultural cooperation issues, 
political issues were not absent. This was made clear yesterday 
in the two lengthy speeches by Prime Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Salam 
al- Majali and Jordan's great guest, Egyptian Prime Minister Dr. 
'Atif Sidqi. The two speeches were marked with an objective 
view of the Arab nation's reality and a sincere desire to 
overcome the state of fragmentation, end differences, and direct 
greater attention to the ties of bilateral cooperation between 
the various Arab countries. 
  Although it is clear that both Jordan and Egypt are facing 
difficult challenges and economic and political pressures here 
and there, that reality in particular provides the motive to 
develop bilateral ties, taking inspiration from the mutual 
interest of the leaders of the two countries, His Majesty King 
Husayn and His Excellency President Muhammad Husni Mubarak, to 
bolster these ties within the context of mutual respect and to 
develop the existing opportunities of cooperation and to explore 
further opportunities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

