<DATE1>  5 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting Continues; Airport Bombed; Calls for Peace Made </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting Continues; Airport Bombed; Calls for Peace Made </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Plan in Place To Evacuate Nationals </H4>

<F P=102> NC0505131394 Paris AFP in English 1242 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0505131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Dubai, May 5 (AFP)--Heavy gunfire broke out 
around Yemen's presidential palace in Sanaa early Thursday and 
rival northern and southern forces bombed the country's two main 
airports in Sanaa and Aden. 
  Diplomatic sources contacted from the United Arab Emirates 
said a plan to evacuate Western nationals could be put into 
action later in the day. 
  No southern units are normally deployed in the capital, but 
a 
Western diplomat was unable to say whether the gunfire round the 
palace of President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih was between factions of 
the northern troops. 
  One source said Sanaa airport had been closed to air traffic 
after being bombed by southern warplanes but that "the runway 
was usable." 
  Anti-aircraft guns blazed into action in Sanaa as southern 
fighter planes loyal to Vice President 'Ali Salim al-Bid dropped 
bombs in a raid on government buildings and the radio and 
television centre there, an AFP correspondent there reported. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

