<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting Continues; Airport Bombed; Calls for Peace Made </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Salih, U.S. Envoy Meet, Discuss Relations </H4>

<F P=102> JN0505183394 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1700 GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0505183394 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brother Lieutenant General 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih, 
chairman of the Presidential Council, received at his office 
today, Robert Pelletreau, U.S. assistant secretary for Near 
Eastern Affairs, who conveyed to the brother president a message 
from the U.S. Administration dealing with bilateral relations, 
fields of cooperation, and issues on interest to both friendly 
countries, in addition to the current developments in our 
country. 
  During the meeting, the two sides reviewed the means of 
promoting bilateral relations and expanding fields of 
cooperation. They also discussed the situation in our country 
in light of the explosve military situation which was caused by 
the secessionist forces rebelling against the constitutional 
legitimacy, particularly some members the Yemeni Socialist Party 
[YSP] leadership, who seek to fragment the homeland and involve 
the sons of our Yemeni people, their Armed Forces, and security 
forces, in the furnace of fighting. 
  The U.S. assistant secretary expressed the United States' 
support for unity and democracy in our country, and its concern 
about all the challenges facing it as a result of the crisis. 
  The brother Presidential Council chairman expressed his 
regret and deep sorrow over the regrettable events in our 
country as a result of the aggressive and adventurous actions by 
the secessionist elements of the YSP leadership which has 
obstinately rejected all good efforts and endeavors to contain 
the crisis and have caused a comprehensive military explosion. 
  The brother president praised the United States' stand and 
support for the Yemeni unity, democracy, and free economy 
approach. He noted that our people greatly appreciate this 
stand. He stressed our country's concern about promoting its 
relations with the United States in the interest of both 
friendly countries. 
  The brother Presidential Council chairman said that the main 
concern for the sons of our Yemeni people and their leadership 
is to build a new Yemen, the Yemen of 22 May 1990, which is 
based on democracy, unity, political and economic freedom, 
social justice, comprehensive development, respect for human 
rights, the planning of institutions, and the building of the 
state of law and order. 
  Attending the meeting were Foreign Minister Muhammad Salim 
Basindwah and U.S. Ambassador in Sanaa Arthur Hughes. 

</TEXT>

