<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Islamic Jihad To Pursue Fight Despite Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Islamic Jihad To Pursue Fight Despite Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0505172294 Amman AL-DUSTUR in Arabic 5 May 94 p 20 </F>
<F P=103> JN0505172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-DUSTUR </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] London: Quds Press--The Islamic Jihad Movement in 
Palestine has stated that it will carry on with its fight 
against Israeli occupation, despite the signing of the agreement 
launching self-rule in Gaza and Jericho. 
  A statement sent by the movement to Quds Press says the 
signing of the agreement "shows how lightly our people's appeals 
have been taken." 
  The movement, which takes a negative view of the peace 
negotiations with Israel, said "the agreement amounts to 
capitulation and will not bring peace." "The causes that 
triggered the intifadah are still there," it emphasized. 
  The agreement 'Arafat and Rabin signed in Cairo yesterday 
skirts the substance of occupation, the Islamic Jihad said. 
This shoddy agreement, the movement's statement warned, lays 
the groundwork for other wars in the region in that it 
represents complete acquiescence in Zionist dictates and terms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58710 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes088dd_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-088 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Oppositionists' Criticism of Agreement Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Oppositionists' Criticism of Agreement Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0605090894 Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network in 
Arabic 0415 GMT 6 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0605090894 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] A general strike was observed in Jerusalem and 
other occupied Arab territories for the second consecutive day 
in protest against the self-rule agreement. A period of general 
mourning, called for by Hamas [Islamic Resistance Movement], 
prevails throughout the occupied Arab territories. 
  News agencies described the atmosphere in the occupied 
territories. They said a state of apprehension and 
disappointment is prevailing in these territories. 
'Abd-al-Karim Sidr, a leading Fatah member in Jericho, 
described the situation in Jericho as inconvenient. He said 
there is Palestinian anxiety because of the large gap between 
Palestinians in the occupied territories and the Palestinian 
team that negotiates with Israel. [passage omitted] 
  Nayif Hawatimah, secretary general of the Democratic Front 
for the Liberation of Palestine, and Dr. George Habash, 
secretary general of the Popular Front for the Liberation of 
Palestine, held a news conference yesterday. They criticized 
the Cairo agreement, saying that it does not meet the 
Palestinian people's demands and that it completely ignores both 
the UN resolutions and international legitimacy. Hawatimah and 
Habash added that this agreement will not be binding on the 
Palestinian people. 
  Ahmad Jibril, secretary general of the Popular Front for the 
Liberation of Palestine-General Command, said the agreement 
would fail within three months. In a statement, Jibril added 
that the Alliance of Palestinian Forces will continue its 
struggle against Israeli occupation. 
  The Islamic Resistance Movement, Hamas, said the self-rule 
agreement bestows legitimacy on occupation, injustice, and 
repression, adding that this agreement will not last long. 
Ibrahim Ghawshah, official Hamas spokesman, stressed the 
failure of the agreement on implementing the self-rule, which 
was signed by 'Arafat and Rabin in Cairo the day before 
yesterday. This agreement will not succeed, he noted. 
  In a statement yesterday, Ghawshah added that the agreement 
does not meet any of the Palestinian people's aspirations and 
demands regarding liberation, repatriation, self-determination, 
and the establishment of a Palestinian state. Instead, the 
agreement increased the Palestinian people's fragmentation and 
revealed the impotence and fragility of the PLO leadership in 
Tunis. Ghawshah said the most serious result of this agreement 
is that it diverted attention from Israeli occupation and 
created tremendous internal contradictions, which Rabin and 
Peres sought to foster when they promptly signed the agreement. 
  Concluding his statement, Ghawshah called on the Palestinian 
people in and outside the occupied territories to close ranks 
and unify their position in order to topple this agreement. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

