<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Calls For Halt to Yemen Fighting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Calls For Halt to Yemen Fighting </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Mubarak Urges `Self-Restraint' </H4>

<F P=102> NC0505212794 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1950 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0505212794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 5 May (MENA)--President Husni Mubarak has 
issued another appeal to the Yemeni leaders to end the fighting. 
He warned of the grave consequences of the spreading 
confrontation between the armed forces in northern and southern 
Yemen and said that the situation is ominous and has been so 
since the start of the current crisis. 
  In his appeal, the president said: Wishing to avoid an armed 
confrontation among the sons of the Yemeni people, I called upon 
you repeatedly to exercise self-restraint, resort to reason, and 
seek understanding and reconciliation through dialogue. With 
this same motive, Egyptian mediation was and still is active. 
I have repeatedly warned of the dangers involved in a clash 
that would be difficult to contain. 
  President Mubarak said: I call on Yemeni President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih to use the powers of his office in making the 
decisions necessary to end the current fighting in the country, 
separate the troops, and deflect the imminent danger the current 
strife portends for all Yemenis. 
  In his appeal, President Mubarak said that a decision to 
halt 
all military operations on both sides and separate the troops 
will thwart the designs of those who conspire against the sons 
of the Yemeni people and their unity and give dialogue, reason, 
and logic a chance to prevail. 
  President Mubarak added: I trust that President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih will side with the interests of the Yemeni 
people and stop the fighting before it turns into a full-fledged 
civil war that would engulf Yemen in great dangers and whose 
complications will be hard to control or reverse. President 
Mubarak said that everyone would place Yemeni interests above 
all considerations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

