<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Musa Comments on Importance of Self-Rule </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Musa Comments on Importance of Self-Rule </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0505154594 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1500 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0505154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Cairo, 5 May (MENA)--Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa 
has stated the importance of the signing of the 
Israeli-Palestinian agreement to implement self-rule in Gaza and 
Jericho, which took place in Cairo yesterday. 
  In remarks he made today, Musa described the agreement as 
"good," noting that it is the first step toward reaching a 
comprehensive solution for the Palestinian issue. Musa pointed 
out that the implementation of the Israeli-Palestinian self-rule 
agreement in Gaza and Jericho will begin in a week or two, with 
the return of Palestinian president Yasir 'Arafat and senior PLO 
officials. He noted that the first step will be implemented in 
Gaza and Jericho, to be followed by extending the Palestinian 
authority over the remaining Palestinian territory in the West 
Bank. He added: Other steps have been agreed upon and we hope 
the pace of the peace process will accelerate to reach the final 
stage as soon as possible and within two years of the 
implementation of the agreement. 
  Musa emphasized that any step toward achieving peace and 
stability in the region will have a positive impact on all the 
region's countries. He noted that Egypt is interested in 
establishing peace and stability in the region. He pointed out 
that if the Arab-Israeli conflict is resolved in accordance with 
the resolutions of the international community and through 
negotiations and agreements among the parties concerned, the 
region will undoubtedly enter a better stage. It will be a 
stage of cooperation and development in which the region's 
peoples can enjoy peace. 
  On U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher's recent talks 
in Damascus, Musa noted that such meetings show Syria's interest 
in the U.S. role regarding the peace process. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

