<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Agrees To Drop Title of `President' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat Agrees To Drop Title of `President' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0505210594 Paris AFP in English 2022 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0505210594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, May 5 (AFP) -- PLO leader Yasir 'Arafat has 
agreed to drop the title "president of Palestine" when he enters 
the self-rule regions of Jericho and the Gaza Strip. 
  According to a letter annexed to the Cairo accord on the 
launch of self-rule signed Wednesday, he will use the title 
"Chairman (Ra'is in Arabic) of the Palestinian Authority" to run 
Gaza and Jericho. 
  The Palestinians have referred to 'Arafat as president of 
Palestine since a session of their parliament-in-exile in 
Algiers in 1988. 
  But the letter, a copy of which AFP received here on 
Thursday 
[5 May], allows the Palestine Liberation Organisation chairman 
to use the Arabic title "Ra'is" which also means president. 
  Also in the letter from Arafat addressed to Israel's Prime 
Minister Yitzhaq Rabin, a co-signatory of the accord, the PLO 
agrees to inform the Israeli government of the names of the 
Palestinian Authority. 
  In Israel, the head of the government press office Uri Dromi 
on Thursday quoted Rabin as telling 'Arafat in Cairo to stop 
globe-trotting and "get prepared for serious things." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

