<H3> <TI>   Cairo, Refugee Talks To Resume; Opposition Reacts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cairo, Refugee Talks To Resume; Opposition Reacts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0605064994 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 0500 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0605064994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Udi Segal -- live] </F>
  [Excerpt] Jerusalem sources have said that negotiations 
with the PLO on the completion of the Gaza and Jericho agreement 
will resume only after the PLO enters the self-government areas. 
Foreign Ministry sources believe that the negotiations will 
resume in Cairo, and will be held on the level they were held so 
far -- delegations under Major General Amnon Shahaq and Dr. 
Nabil Sha'th. 
  Speaking in Cairo, Sha'th announced that negotiations on the 
return of tens of thousands of misplaced Palestinians from 1967 
will begin next month. Jerusalem confirmed that the 
negotiations will be held according to the Oslo agreement in a 
four-way committee of representatives from Israel, the PLO, 
Egypt, and Jordan. According to Sha'th, Jordan has agreed to 
participate in the talks at the beginning of next month. 
  Foreign Ministry sources said that they do not know that a 
date has been set for the convention of the committee, but they 
said that Israel has agreed in principle that the committee 
convene in some two months. [passage omitted] 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 0600 GMT on 6 May adds: 
"Tzomet Chairman Refa'el Eytan says that there never were 
200,000 Palestinian refugees of the Six-Days War. There were 
only several dozen thousands [as heard], mostly from three 
villages from the Latrun region." Eytan further says that "the 
public is being misled, and that through these refugees, the 
government wants to grant the Palestinians the right of return 
it had canceled in the past. 
  ["The Likud says that the government no longer serves Jewish 
and Zionists interests, as seen in its readiness to implement 
the Palestinian right of return. The Likud spokesman has said 
that returning hundreds of thousands of Palestinian refugees 
into the boundaries of Eretz Yisra'el will result in a 
demographic disaster for Israel."] 

</TEXT>

