<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arab League Holds Emergency Session on Yemen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Arab League Holds Emergency Session on Yemen </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Arab League Decides Not to Intervene </H4>

<F P=102> NC0705133994 Paris AFP in English 1304 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0705133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, May 7 (AFP) -- The Arab League decided here 
Saturday [7 May] not to intervene in Yemen's civil war after the 
northern-led government turned down an Egyptian proposal to send 
Arab peacekeepers to halt its conflict with the south. 
  But permanent delegates at the Cairo-based organisation 
called on its secretary general, 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid, to pursue 
efforts to end the conflict which erupted on Thursday. 
  A diplomatic source said the League decided to abstain on 
the 
Egyptian proposal after it had been turned down by the north. 
  Senior southern leader 'Abd-al-Aziz al-Dali had said earlier 
the south could favour Egyptian proposals to send a peacekeeping 
force. 
  He said the southern Yemen Socialist Party (YSP) led by 
Vice-President 'Ali Salim al-Bid "supported all measures by the 
Arab League," after meeting with 'Abd-al-Majid. 
  And he added that if the "situation is necessary and if it 
is 
imperative in order to stop the fighting" then the YSP was in 
favour of sending a peacekeeping force "even if northern leaders 
reject it." 
  Foreign Minister Muhammad Salih Basindwa earlier opposed the 
emergency meeting in Cairo, insisting the three days of intense 
fighting in Yemen was an "internal affair." 
  'Abd-al-Majid told journalists after the meeting behind 
closed doors that the Arab countries had charged him with 
"continuing efforts to stop the fighting immediately." 
  They also repeated their support for Yemen, where fighting 
erupted Thursday between rival forces from the former North and 
South Yemen which were unified in May 1990. 
  The proposal put forward by Egyptian Foreign Minister 'Amr 
Musa needed the backing of both the Arab League and Yemen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58777 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes089bb_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-089 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arab League Holds Emergency Session on Yemen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Arab League Holds Emergency Session on Yemen </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    'Abd-al-Majid Holds News Conference </H4>

<F P=102> NC0705140994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1315 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0705140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 7 May (MENA)--The Arab League Council held an 
emergency session in Cairo today. It called on Yemeni leaders 
to work harder to resolve their differences and cement Yemeni 
unity, pointing out that Yemen's unity is linked to the region's 
stability and security. This was declared by Arab League 
Secretary General Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid at a news conference 
following the end of the session. 
  Yemen's unity is a "pan-Arab achievement and asset" that 
must 
be protected and maintained, Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid said. The 
secretary general said that the Arab League Council instructed 
him to get in touch with Yemeni leaders to seek an immediate end 
to the fighting and to keep the League's member states informed 
about his efforts. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid said that the Council will consider itself 
in a state of permanent session to follow up the efforts that 
various Arab leaders are exerting to end the Yemeni crisis. 
  Answering journalists' questions, Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid said 
that 
the dispatch of Arab troops to separate rival forces in Yemen 
"was not discussed" in today's session. 
  Asked to comment on the news that Yemen is not enthusiastic 
about the holding of this particular meeting of the Arab League 
Council, the secretary general said that any two League member 
states have the right to request a Council meeting. Today's 
session was at the request of Egypt and Libya, he stated. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid said that the Arab League Council does not 
interfere in the internal affairs of Yemen or any Arab country. 
The Council respects the sovereignty of all Arab countries, he 
added. 
  The secretary general pointed out that the Yemeni leadership 
received an Arab League delegation on 4 March. Dr. 
'Abd-al-Majid pointed out that the other Arab leaders attended 
the signing of the Pledge and Accord document in Amman, on 20 
February, a matter which, the secretary general added, confirms 
Arab interest in the situation in Yemen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

