<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Denies Asking For Delay in Power Transfer </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat Denies Asking For Delay in Power Transfer </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0605182594 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1715 GMT 6 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0605182594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Muhammad Kurayshan report from Tunis] </F>
  [Text] The PLO Executive Committee is expected to resume 
meetings in Tunis tomorrow. The Executive committee began its 
meetings today under Yasir 'Arafat and in the presence of nine 
of its members. Yasir 'Abd-Rabbuh and Bishop Iliya Khuri will 
join them tomorrow. 
  Immediately after his return from Amman, 'Arafat submitted a 
report on the atmosphere that prevailed over the signing of the 
Cairo agreement on 4 May, particularly on the points of 
differences that are still pending with the Israelis. 'Arafat 
said these differences will be discussed within the next three 
months. 
  According to informed sources here, 'Arafat denied at the 
meeting that he had asked Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin 
to postpone the transfer of power in Gaza and Jericho until the 
Palestinian side finds itself ready to do so. 
  The PLO Executive Committee discussed the configuration of 
the Palestinian authority that will take charge of the autonomy 
rule, which is expected to be equally divided between the 
Palestinians inside and outside the [territories] under Yasir 
'Arafat. 
  The formation of this authority is expected to be announced 
here in Tunis in the next two days, at the end of the current 
meetings. It seems that there is no dispute about the figures 
from the territories, while viewpoints continue to be exchanged 
concerning the figures from the diaspora [word indistinct] from 
the PLO Executive Committee and Fatah Central Committee. 
  Ahmad Quray', Abu-'Ala', head of the PLO Economic 
Department, will leave for Amman soon to inform the Jordanian 
Government about the details of the economic agreement with 
Israel and the scope of Jordanian-Palestinian coordination in 
this field. 

</TEXT>

