<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Jets to Pakistan Would Spur `Deep Concern' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Jets to Pakistan Would Spur `Deep Concern' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0905112494 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 9 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0905112494 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] India would have to reappraise the country's 
defense requirements and take adequate steps to safeguard its 
security in view of Pakistan's acquisition of sophisticated 
military equipment. The minister of state for external affairs, 
Mr. Salman Khurshid, told the Lok Sabha during question hour 
today that the government has conveyed that the U.S. proposal to 
transfer F-16 aircraft and other military equipment to Pakistan 
is a matter of deep concern for India. In a written reply, the 
minister said the U.S. Government has not pressed for nuclear 
capping by India as they have proposed to Pakistan as a 
condition to supplying F-16 fighters. 
  In another written reply, Mr. Salman Khurshid informed the 
house that the government has consistently maintained that it 
will not sign the NPT [Nonproliferation Treaty] in its present 
form because of its discriminatory nature. Referring to the 
efforts by the U.S. administration to modify the Pressler 
Amendment, the minister said latest reports indicate that these 
efforts have not been successful. 

</TEXT>

