<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   IDF General: No Timetable Yet for Gaza Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IDF General: No Timetable Yet for Gaza Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0805185594 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1800 GMT 8 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0805185594 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Major General Matan Vilna'i, commander of the 
Southern Command, has said there is as yet no timetable for the 
withdrawal from the Gaza Strip. The area will be handed over to 
the Palestinians only after three conditions are met: the IDF 
[Israel Defense Forces] fully completes its deployment to 
protect the Jewish settlements, a liaison mechanism is set up, 
and the Palestinians are ready to enter the area. 
  Gen. Vilna'i said that according to plans, Palestinian 
policemen will enter the Gaza Strip within the next few days and 
that the IDF will hand over to them some 30 facilities formerly 
used by the IDF, the Prison Authority, and the Israel Police. 
He added that there will be no overlap in responsibility for 
the area, and that responsibility will be transferred in its 
entirety at a specific time. The transfer of powers will not be 
accompanied by joint Israeli-Palestinian ceremonies to prevent 
tempers from flaring, he noted. 
  Maj. Gen. 'Uzi Dayan, head of the General Staff's Planning 
Branch and a participant in the Cairo talks, said that all the 
points important to Israel had been safeguarded in the security 
segment of the Gaza-Jericho agreement. Our correspondent 
Karmela Menashe reports that the two generals were speaking at a 
news conference in Tel Aviv. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

