<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fadlallah on Gaza-Jericho, U.S. Role in Yemen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fadlallah on Gaza-Jericho, U.S. Role in Yemen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0805172994 Beirut Radio Lebanon in Arabic 1530 GMT 8 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0805172994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Radio Lebanon </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Commenting on the signing of the Palestinian-Israeli 
agreement, 'Allamah Sayyid Muhammad Husayn Fadlallah said that 
the agreement was a victory for Israel, not the Palestinians. 
Israel, Fadlallah pointed out, polished its public image and 
got many doors open in the Arab World. Dazzled by the 
agreement, some Arabs are opening their doors to Israel and 
hastening to normalize relations with it even before the latter 
makes any overture. 
  Fadlallah added: The Arab world is under a spell. Israel is 
not offering the Arabs much. The enemy's prime minister told a 
Qatari newspaper: We want to be stronger than the Arabs so that 
the latter may understand that they cannot get anything from us 
except through negotiations. 
  This, Fadlallah said, means that America helped Israel 
militarily so as to force the Arabs to make concessions. 
America wanted to deprive the Arabs of any clout they may use 
against Israel. 
  Therefore, this agreement has no legitimacy. We believe that 
the nation should hold firm to its principles, because once we 
start making concessions we will never stop. We might even lose 
more land. 
  France once saw Algeria as French territory. America may 
come to see the Gulf as U.S. territory. We recently read that a 
U.S. official visited Yemen and no sooner was he gone than the 
war broke out there. We in Lebanon are used to such visits by 
U.S. officials, who are adept at playing a double game. This 
double game, long known to us in Lebanon, has just started in 
Yemen. 

</TEXT>

