<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Southern Forces Attack Targets in Sanaa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Southern Forces Attack Targets in Sanaa </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Scuds Fired at Sanaa </H4>

<F P=102> NC0605180794 Paris AFP in English 1758 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0605180794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, May 6 (AFP)--Southern forces fired six Scud 
long-range missiles at economic and civilian targets in Yemen's 
capital on Friday, but without causing damage or casualties, the 
northern General People's Congress (GPC) said. 
  A GPC spokesman, quoted by the official news agency SABA', 
said one of the missiles exploded near Sanaa international 
airport and another three in mountainous areas. It gave no 
location for the other two. 
  "These missiles caused only horror for children, women and 
the elderly," said the spokesman, warning that the southern 
forces of the Yemen Socialist Party would be tried for war 
crimes. 
  He denied earlier reports from the south that the 
presidential palace in Sanaa had been hit. 
  With Yemen's four-year-old union in peril, President 'Ali 
Abdallah Salih's GPC has said its troops are bearing down on the 
southern port city of Aden with the aim of capturing it. 
  The forces of Salih, a northerner, are locked in a bitter 
struggle with those of Vice President 'Ali Salim al-Bid, a 
southerner, who was dismissed by parliament on Thursday night at 
the end of a first day of heavy fighting. 
  Southern officials said their planes had hit the 
presidential 
palace with missiles and set it ablaze. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

