<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister: Northern Forces Have Upper Hand </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister: Northern Forces Have Upper Hand </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0705105994 Paris AFP in English 1044 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0705105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Doha, May 7 (AFP) -- Yemeni Foreign Minister 
Muhammad Salih Basindwah called on southern leaders to surrender 
Saturday [7 May] saying northern forces had the upper hand as 
fighting raged near Aden. 
  Basindwah, a northerner, told Qatar's state-run radio that 
southern forces loyal to Vice-President 'Ali Salim al-Bid had 
fired 13 Scud missiles at the capital Sanaa since fighting 
erupted on Thursday. 
  But he said northern forces backing President 'Ali 'Abdallah 
Salih still had the advantage, saying 12 southern al-Bid 
warplanes had been shot down since Thursday. 
  "The military situation is not developing in the favour" of 
southern leaders he said, calling on them to "turn themselves in 
immediately", pledging that they would receive "a fair trial." 
  "Fierce fighting is raging near Aden," the main southern 
port- city, "between the (northern) army and the rebels", 
Basindwah said in a reference to al-Bid's forces. 
  He added that Aden was under a northern blockade to "force 
the outlaws to surrender." 
  Diplomats in Yemen said that a large concentration of 
northern troops was seen 50 kilometres (35 miles) north of Aden. 
  Meanwhile Basindwah said the situation in Sanaa and all the 
northern provinces was "calm." 
  He also said northern Yemenis were opposed to an emergency 
meeting of the Arab League to discuss the spiralling civil war 
as it was an "internal affair." 
  His comments came just before the Arab League was due to 
hold 
an emergency meeting in Cairo to discuss an Egyptian proposal to 
send a peacekeeping force to Yemen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

