<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clashes Spread to Aden, Surrounding Areas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clashes Spread to Aden, Surrounding Areas </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Aden `Expected To Fall Within Hours' </H4>

<F P=102> NC0805154694 Paris AFP in English 1529 GMT 8 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0805154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] SANAA, May 8 (AFP) - The battle for Aden reached the 
gates of the southern stronghold on Sunday [8 May] and the city 
was expected to fall under northern control within hours, the 
official Yemeni news agency SABA'' said. 
  "Violent clashes are now taking place at the gates of the 
city between government forces and rebel troops," said SABA'', 
which is run by the northern administration loyal to President 
'Ali 'Abdallah Salih. 
  "Aden is expected to fall within hours," under a barrage of 
tankfire and artillery, it said, reporting fires had broken out 
around the city. 
  SABA'' said a southern brigade had been destroyed in Abyan 
province near Aden and two of the south's warplanes shot down as 
the north seized control of al-Dhalih, a town 60 kilometrers (25 
miles) north of the port city. 
  Despite the northern reports of military success, the 
situation in Aden itself was still calm, according to an AFP 
correspondent in the city of more than 500,000 residents. 
  Diplomats in the region, meanwhile, said the north had 
trapped Aden in a "pincer movement" and captured the south's 
main air base. 
  But the south said it repelled northern forces in al-Kawt, 
30 
kilometres (18 miles) to the east of Aden and that Salih's 
troops were in retreat toward the mountains. 
  Other northern elements had been ambushed and wiped out in 
Radfan, to the north, said military spokesmen in Aden, the power 
base of Vice President 'Ali Salim al-Bid, the president's bitter 
rival. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

