<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sanaa Paper Reports 12,000 Casualties in Fighting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sanaa Paper Reports 12,000 Casualties in Fighting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0905055094 Amman Radio Jordan in English 0430 GMT 9 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN0905055094 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rival Yemeni armies battled for a sixth day today in 
a bloody confrontation shredding the volatile state's 
three-year-old unity. A Yemeni military spokesman in Sanaa has 
said that fierce fighting was under way in the southern 
provinces of Aden and Lahij. The spokesman said that the four 
brigades of the northern army were advancing on Aden and 
predicted the city would fall today. But in a radio broadcast, 
the south denied that northern forces had reached the outskirts 
of Aden where a general mobilization had been ordered to defend 
the city. 
  Meanwhile, the English language YEMEN TIMES, published in 
Sanaa, reported that 12,000 people had been already killed or 
wounded in the fighting, but it gave no source. 
  On the other hand, Western embassies in Sanaa said that they 
were planning further evacuations today. About 230 British and 
Commonwealth nationals were expected to leave. The United 
States, Germany, Italy, and French Embassies had similar plans, 
but gave no numbers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

