<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-089 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   AL-AHRAM Regrets Developments in Yemen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    AL-AHRAM Regrets Developments in Yemen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0705081094 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0605 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0705081094 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 7 May (MENA)--AL-AHRAM newspaper regrets what 
is happening in Yemen. It says it is difficult for an Arab to 
see brothers shed each other's blood in the same country, 
destroying everything that the one Yemeni people have both in 
the north and south. 
  In today's editorial, the paper notes that since it began a 
few months ago the Yemeni crisis has portended grave 
consequences and that it entails grave dangers, especially since 
the exchange of air bombardments in Aden and Sanaa and 
resolutions declaring the vice president illegitimate and 
dismissing the defense minister. 
  The paper says the Arabs have not learned much from the hard 
lessons they have suffered in their modern history. What is 
happening in Yemen is the best proof of this, as the Declaration 
of Unity through harmony and peace is retracted and replaced by 
war and conflict. 
  The newspaper notes Egypt's efforts to contain the Yemeni 
crisis before it worsens. President Mubarak, it says, has sent 
an envoy who has almost become a resident there. So far he has 
addressed two appeals to the Yemeni brothers to stop subjecting 
their country to destruction, but all this has been in vain. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

