<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sidqi on Dialogue With Terrorists, Foreign Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sidqi on Dialogue With Terrorists, Foreign Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0605183394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1755 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0605183394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Amman, 6 May (MENA)--Prime Minister Dr. 'Atif 
Sidqi stated that Egypt's leadership and security organs are 
confronting terrorism and terrorists with the firmness and 
strength they deserve and that all their activities are 
confronted decisively. He said: We should not worry about Egypt. 
  Speaking at a meeting with members of the Egyptian community 
in Jordan before leaving Amman this afternoon, the prime 
minister said that compared with other countries, terrorism in 
Egypt is decreasing in a big way. 
  Answering a question, he said that attempts were made over a 
long period to hold a dialogue with these terrorists at times 
between 1980 and 1987 or 1988. He added: The dialogue 
continued in one way or another but they were not ready to 
listen to the voice of reason and their ideas rendered the 
dialogue useless. When they started to use bullets and kill, the 
security organs confronted them decisively and firmly. 
  Dr. Sidqi stressed that achieving a lasting, just, and 
honorable peace in the region lies at the core of Egypt's 
policy. He said: Egypt welcomes the Israeli-Palestinian 
Agreement signed in Cairo on Wednesday on the basis that it is a 
step toward the comprehensive solution for all the countries in 
the region. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

