<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lebanese-Syrian Summit Prompted by U.S. Message </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lebanese-Syrian Summit Prompted by U.S. Message </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0605133094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 6 May 94 p4 </F>
<F P=103> PM0605133094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Salwa al-Ustuwani: "Lebanese-Syrian Summit Held </F>
Suddenly in Damascus After U.S. Message to President al-Hirawi"] 
  [Excerpts] Beirut, London, Damascus -- Yesterday attention 
was focused on the Lebanese-Syrian summit held in Damascus and 
the investigation of crimes committed against the state's 
internal security and related reactions. [passage omitted] 
  The arrangements for the summit were made after a meeting 
held between Lebanese President al-Hirawi and U.S. Ambassador in 
Beirut Mark Hambley. 
  Responsible Syrian sources in Damascus have stated that the 
two presidents discussed and held consultations on the new 
developments in the region and the results of Christopher's 
visit and the Israeli proposals and ideas he brought with him on 
the peace process, withdrawals from the Golan, dismantling of 
the settlements, and especially the Lebanese question. They 
also discussed the position of the two countries regarding the 
current contacts for the resumption of the negotiations in 
Washington, which is what Christopher is now working for, 
particularly since the final signing of the Gaza-Jericho 
agreement. 
  The two sides also reviewed the situation in Lebanon and 
bilateral relations. The arrival of President al-Hirawi, 
Speaker Birri, and Prime Minister al-Hariri was sudden and came 
after a meeting in Beirut between President al-Hirawi and the 
U.S. ambassador who delivered a message to him from Washington 
on the peace process. According to Lebanese sources, the 
message dealt with the situation in southern Lebanon and called 
on Lebanon to seek a settlement with Israel, disarm Hizballah, 
and put an end to the Lebanese resistance against Israel and its 
collaborators. 
  Presidents al-Asad and al-Hirawi reaffirmed coordination of 
their positions and effective moves to face the negative 
consequences of the Gaza-Jericho agreement. 
  The sources believe that the U.S. message upset the Lebanese 
leaders who immediately went to Damascus to discuss the 
situation. The message warned that Israel might continue its 
scorched-earth policy and carry out more score-settling 
operations unless the Lebanese officials quickly cool the 
situation in the south and unless they rejoin the peace process. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

