<H3> <TI>   Japanese Foreign Minister Pays Official Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japanese Foreign Minister Pays Official Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Further on al-Shar'-Kakizawa Talks </H4>

<F P=102> OW0705011394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0059 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0705011394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Damascus, May 6 KYODO -- Syria's Foreign Minister 
Faruq al-Shar' told Japanese Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa on 
Friday [6 May] that Syria is negative about joining multilateral 
peace talks in the Middle East peace process at the present 
stage. 
  In a 105-minute meeting with al-Shar', Kakizawa urged Syria 
to join the multilateral talks, Japanese officials said. 
Al-Shar', however, told Kakizawa that Syria will be pleased to 
join the talks if peace is achieved. But the talks will be 
vulnerable if peace is not achieved, al-Shar' was quoted as 
saying. Al-Shar' hinted at Damascus' position to demand a 
complete return of the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights. 
  The Syrian foreign minister also argued that Mideast 
problems 
must be settled in line with UN Security Council resolutions 
that stipulate the inviolability of territories for all Mideast 
countries, the officials said. Al-Shar' offered his "personal 
support" for Japan's bid to obtain a permanent seat in the UN 
Security Council, saying that he will recommend the Syrian 
government to show support. 
  Kakizawa flew to Damascus from Amman on Friday. 

</TEXT>

