<H3> <TI>   Japanese Foreign Minister Pays Official Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japanese Foreign Minister Pays Official Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kakizawa Asks al-Asad To Join Peace Talks </H4>

<F P=102> OW0705123594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1157 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0705123594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Damascus, May 7 KYODO -- Japanese Foreign Minister 
Koji Kakizawa on Saturday [7 May] asked Syrian President Hafiz 
Al-Asad to join multilateral talks in the Middle East peace 
process, Japanese officials said. 
  During the 30-minute meeting, Kakizawa told Al-Asad that he 
is looking forward to a positive proposal to facilitate further 
Israeli steps in the peace talks, the officials said. 
  But they did not disclose immediately how Al-Asad responded. 
On Friday, Syria's Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar' told 
Kakizawa that Syria is negative about joining the multilateral 
talks at the present stage. 
  Al-Asad expressed his support for Japan's bid to obtain a 
permanent seat in the U.N. Security Council, the officials said. 
  Al-Asad said he backs Japan's move, adding, "I expect Japan 
to tackle (international) issues from a fair position," they 
said. Kakizawa also asked Al-Asad to pay an early visit to 
Japan. The Syrian president promised to make efforts to meet 
Japan's request, the officials said. 
  The meeting with Al-Asad concluded Kakizawa's two-day visit 
to Syria on the final leg of a weeklong Middle East tour which 
took him to Egypt, Israel, Jordan and the Israeli-occupied 
territories . 
  He will return to Tokyo on Sunday. 

</TEXT>

