<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Proceedings of Joint Committee With Egypt Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Proceedings of Joint Committee With Egypt Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    More on News Conference </H4>

<F P=102> JN0705144394 Amman AL-RA'Y in Arabic 7 May 94 pp 1, 26 </F>
<F P=103> JN0705144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-RA'Y </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Caroline Faraj] </F>
  [Excerpts] AL-RA'Y -- Prime Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Salam 
al-Majali has said that the Palestinian brothers achieved a 
major step in Cairo. [passage omitted] This came in a joint 
news conference held at the Prime Ministry yesterday by Prime 
Minister Dr. al-Majali and Egyptian Prime Minister Dr. 'Atif 
Sidqi at the conclusion of the meetings of the Joint 
Jordanian-Egyptian Higher Committee. [passage omitted] 
  Asked about Egyptian-Palestinian relations and the news 
reports that Egypt should first approve of any Palestinian 
decision before it is announced, Dr. Sidqi denied these reports, 
saying: Egypt places itself, its resources, and its experience 
at the disposal of any Arab country. Therefore, it is natural 
to place our resources and experience at the disposal of the 
Palestinians, particularly the PLO. 
  Dr. Sidqi added: However, it is incorrect to say that no 
Palestinian decisions are made without referring to Egypt. 
Palestinian decisions are made by the Palestinians themselves. 
We only help and express our opinions, which are sometimes 
taken into consideration and sometimes not. We have never 
imposed anything on the PLO since the time it was recognized as 
the sole, legitimate representative of the Palestinian people 
inside and outside [the occupied territory]. 
  Dr. Sidqi indicated that Egypt has been maintaining good 
relations with the PLO for a long time. He said: Relations 
between us and the PLO have never been completely severed. Even 
during times of disagreement, contacts were held. The Palestine 
question is the heart of the Middle East issue. Therefore, it 
is in our common interest that we hold almost daily talks and 
consultations. [passage omitted] 
  In response to a question on whether Jordan has asked Egypt 
to intervene with the United States to lift the al-'Aqabah 
siege, Dr. Sidqi said: There is no mediation in this regard. 
  He added: We do, however, welcome the recent developments 
aimed at finding a solution to this problem because it harms 
Jordan. Egypt is ready to intervene and mediate should the need 
arise. However, the current proposals respond to most of 
Jordan's wishes and legitimate demands. This fact is supported 
by Egypt. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

