<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Hariri Decides To Stay Home, Refrain From Work </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Hariri Decides To Stay Home, Refrain From Work </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Action Described as `Political Stance' </H4>

<F P=102> NC0805180994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1710 GMT 8 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0805180994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beirut, 8 May (MENA)--Semi-official Lebanese 
sources have stated that Prime Minister Rafiq al-Hariri has 
decided to stay home and to refrain from doing his work in what 
these sources have described as a political stance and not a 
constitutional one. No official statement has yet been issued 
by the prime minister on the reasons for his decision to remain 
at home. However, informed sources have told the MENA 
correspondent that Prime Minister al-Hariri is facing 
difficulties in reshuffling his cabinet with a view to improving 
the chances of Christian representation in the Lebanese 
Government to remedy the frustration felt by the Christians in 
Lebanon. 
  The sources said al-Hariri's decision does not mean he will 
resign. The MENA correspondent says several ministers, as well 
as political, religious, and military figures, including Army 
Commander Gen. Emile Lahhud, have visited al-Hariri at his 
mansion in the Quraytim area of Beirut to ask him to change his 
mind. 
  Informed sources in Beirut say al-Hariri's decision to stop 
doing his job has moved what could be considered a cabinet 
crisis into the Lebanese streets. In the past few days there 
has been a lot of speculation in the press and in political 
quarters about an imminent cabinet reshuffle to include some 
Christian political figures in the government, such as 
Phalangist Party leader Dr. George Sa'adah, plus a member from 
the National Liberal Party and other Christian figures. 
  The situation is still vague regarding the fate of the 
Lebanese Government. Prime Minister al-Hariri canceled a radio 
and television interview that was scheduled to be aired live 
tonight, in which he would have addressed questions and 
speculations about a possible cabinet reshuffle. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58913 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes089_j_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-089 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<H3> <TI>   GCC States Call On Yemenis To End Fighting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    GCC States Call On Yemenis To End Fighting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0705191694 Kuwait KUNA in Arabic 1730 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0705191694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait KUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riyadh, 7 May (KUNA) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council 
[GCC] member-states have called on the Yemeni leaders to respond 
"to the initiatives calling for an end to the fighting and to 
resort to reason and dialogue to solve their differences". 
  A statement issued after the meeting of the GCC foreign 
ministers or their representatives, which was held here today, 
called on the leaders of Yemen to put the interests of Yemen and 
its people above all considerations and stop the battles, 
fighting and practise utmost self-restraint to spare blood and 
protect lives and property. 
  In the statement, the GCC member-states expressed their 
strong anxiety and regret "about the dangerous and painful 
impending breakdown witnessed by the Republic of Yemen as a 
result of the battles and fighting that broke out between 
brothers." 
  The foreign ministers of Kuwait, Bahrain, the Kingdom of 
Saudi Arabia, the UAE, and the ambassadors of the State of Qatar 
and the Sultanate of Oman -- who acted for the foreign ministers 
who will arrive here later -- met here at midday today. 
  Diplomatic sources said that the meeting tackled the 
preparations for the 5th meeting of the GCC's foreign ministers 
and their counterparts in the European Union, which will be held 
here tomorrow, in addition to the current situation in Yemen. 
  They pointed out that the final statement, which will be 
issued tomorrow, will include reference to the events that 
erupted in Yemen last week. 
  The sources added that the meeting dealt with some of the 
points included in the EU's proposals and will be discussed 
tomorrow. 
  They said that the Council's foreign ministers had 
coordinated among themselves to respond to these points so that 
an agreement, which would contribute to the development of 
relations between the two sides, could be reached. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58914 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes089_j_94002" </HT>


