Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Protest Lodged Against U.S. Treatment of Delegation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Protest Lodged Against U.S. Treatment of Delegation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0605130894 Tehran IRNA in English 1230 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0605130894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, May 6, IRNA -- The Islamic Republic last 
night condemned the American officials' mistreatment of Iranian 
delegation to the joint spring session of the International 
Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank (WB) in Washington on April 
22. 
  The Iranian interests section in Washington in a 
strongly-worded letter to the U.S. foreign affairs department 
through the Pakistani embassy, described as "insulting" the way 
customs officials at Washington airport behaved with Iranian 
Minister of Economy and Finance Morteza Mohammad-Khani and 
Governor of Central Bank Mohammad Hoseyn 'Adeli. 
  The U.S. Customs officials stopped the two senior Iranian 
diplomats, re-checked their suitcases and took photographs from 
them. 
  The letter voicing dissatisfaction, said the treatment not 
only violated the basic diplomatic principles but contradicted 
the U.S. Government's responsibility towards international 
organizations based in America. 
  It continued that U.S. Customs officials had repeatedly 
shown 
such disrespect for Iranian officials visiting America for 
international sessions. 
  The letter expected that the U.S. as a country which hosts 
international sessions would put an end to such practice. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

