<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th: Palestinians Will Control Foreign Affairs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sha'th: Palestinians Will Control Foreign Affairs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0905150994 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 8 May 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM0905150994 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Sawsan Abu-Husayn report: "Nabil Sha'th Tells AL-SHARQ </F>
AL-AWSAT: Palestinian Foreign Affairs Will Not Be Under Israeli 
Control"] 
  [Text] Cairo -- Dr. Nabil Sha'th, adviser to Palestinian 
President Yasir 'Arafat, has confirmed that Yasir 'Arafat is 
ready to take over the national authority this week. He said 
that executive steps have already begun for the assumption of 
national authority and that Palestinian police units will begin 
to arrive in Gaza and Jericho. The vanguards of these forces, 
he said, have reached the Egyptian-Palestinian border. 
  In a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT, Sha'th explained the 
"agreement, emphasizing that it is much better than the 
Declaration of Principles because there have been many 
amendments. If those opposed to the agreement knew these 
amendments well, they would change their minds because the 
agreement is very different from the Declaration of Principles. 
[quotation mark as published] 
  He stressed that the agreement was, for the first time, 
signed by the PLO and the state of Israel and that it was agreed 
to call the national authority the Palestinian Authority. That 
authority will implement all the international agreements 
concluded by the PLO. That authority, he said, will have the 
right to take charge of foreign affairs, which, in other words, 
will not be under Israeli control. The Palestinian Authority 
will have the right to have representative offices abroad in 
addition to the existing embassies of the state of Palestine 
throughout the world. 
  As an example of the Palestinian Authority handling its own 
foreign affairs, Sha'th cited the agreement he signed with U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher on aid in the transfer of 
authority, to the tune of $5 million and 200 police vehicles. 
  He said the agreement consisted of three parts: The first is 
the agreement itself, the second consists of four appendices, 
and the third consists of exchanged letters. They complement 
one another "and we can say that this agreement is a first step 
that will lead to other steps related to Jerusalem, the 
repatriation of refugees, the area of Jericho, and the 
settlements." He added that "in the transitional period the PLO 
will work on the Jerusalem issue to ensure that our rights in it 
are not eroded." 
  He also said: The Palestinian-Israeli agreement is a prelude 
to comprehensive peace based on Security Council Resolutions 242 
and 338, and not as claimed by certain people who try to cast 
doubt. 
  He descsribed what has been published about formation of an 
authority council as mere speculation, noting that the PLO's 
Executive Committee was in continuous session for the purpose of 
setting up the authority. 
  On the powers of the Palestinian Authority, Sha'th said that 
Palestinian officials would have a right to stop and detain an 
Israeli suspect and then hand him over to the Israeli 
authorities, and also prohibit possession of arms by members of 
the public without a license. 
  On the date of 'Arafat's departure for Jericho, he said: 
That will be announced minutes before it takes place. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58930 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes090dd_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-090 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Najjab Criticizes Self-Rule Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Najjab Criticizes Self-Rule Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0905164694 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Arabic 1430 GMT 9 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0905164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with PLO Executive Committee member </F>
Sulayman al-Najjab, in Amman, by Sa'id Mu'addi from the "With 
the Events" program; date not given -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Mu'addi] Mr. Sulayman al-Najjab, PLO Executive 
Committee member, currently in Amman: You boycotted the 
Executive Committee meetings. You also refuse to take part in 
the Palestinian authority. What is the reason? 
  [Al-Najjab] I did not attend the Executive Committee 
meetings, which were devoted to endorsing decisions that were 
made without consultation with the Executive Committee. I 
announced that I would not take part in the Palestinian 
authority under the agreement recently signed in Cairo. This 
authority would remain under the control of the Israeli military 
government, and it is rather similar to a civil administration. 
That is why I refused to participate in this authority. 
  [Mu'addi] What is the solution, and what should Yasir 
'Arafat do in this phase? Why does the minority not comply with 
the majority's decision? 
  [Al-Najjab] Many Executive Committee members are not 
attending the meetings being held in Tunis. I am fully 
convinced that this agreement will not succeed in achieving any 
of the Palestinian people's national objectives. This agreement 
will not improve the Palestinian people's living conditions. 
Our people will continue to adhere to their goal regarding 
national independence and solving the refugees' issue in 
accordance with UN resolutions. 
  [Mu'addi] You are the [Palestinian] People's Party's 
representative in the Executive Committee. What is the 
alternative to the Israeli-Palestinian agreement? 
  [Al-Najjab] As you know, I believe that we have long been 
demanding a peaceful settlement of both the Arab-Israeli 
conflict and the Palestinian-Israeli dispute based on 
implementing the pertinent UN resolutions, particularly the 
Security Council resolutions. This agreement is not a phased or 
final solution. The solution, or the alternative, is to hold 
more serious negotiations, which should be based on the 
resolutions of international legitimacy and which should seek 
their implementation, rather than to avoid the implementation 
of, or commitment to, these resolutions. 
  What is required is to secure Israeli withdrawal as 
stipulated by the Security Council resolutions. The 
Gaza-Jericho arrangements, or agreement, have nothing to do with 
implementing the UN resolutions. This agreement, rather, seeks 
to entrench the current situation. 
  [Mu'addi] Mr. Sulayman al-Najjab: There are Palestinian 
figures from the West Bank and Gaza Strip who refuse to join the 
future Palestinian authority. What is your comment? 
  [Al-Najjab] What you indicate proves that this agreement has 
not convinced anyone that it will secure even a temporary 
solution. The alternative is to search for a solution that will 
secure the Palestinian people's rights. Such a solution can be 
achieved if the Israeli side commits itself to Resolution 242 
and to the fact that any phased settlements are only 
preparations and steps on the path of implementing Resolution 
242. 
  [Mu'addi] But there is an agreement signed by the two sides 
regarding the transitional phase. 
  [Al-Najjab] If the Palestinian people, or their majority, do 
not accept this agreement, then it cannot be implemented. There 
are many examples in this regard. The fate of any solution that 
does not secure both the Palestinian people's rights and the 
actual interests of both sides would... [sentence incomplete as 
heard] 
  [Mu'addi] Mr. Sulayman al-Najjab, Executive Committee 
member, currently in Amman: Thank you very much. 
  [Al-Najjab] You are very welcome, Sa'id. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

