<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Agrees To Receive Arab League Team </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Agrees To Receive Arab League Team </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0905111494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1000 GMT 9 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0905111494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 9 May (MENA)--Ambassador Nayif Sa'ud al-Qadi, 
Jordan's permanent representative to the Arab League and 
chairman of the current Arab League Council emergency session on 
the Yemeni crisis, has denied media reports of differences 
between the Yemeni leadership and the Arab League Council 
regarding the convening of the emergency session to discuss an 
end to the recent fighting there. 
  He told MENA that in a telephone conversation with Arab 
League Secretary General Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid, the Yemeni 
foreign minister welcomed the Arab League Council decision to 
continue its efforts and contacts to stop the fighting between 
the sons of the homeland. The Yemeni foreign minister's 
statement that the Yemeni crisis is an internal affair, as cited 
by news media, does not mean a rejection of the Arab League's 
help in ending the fighting, he said. 
  The ambassador said the Arab League is continuing its 
contacts with the Yemeni and Arab leaders in an attempt to stop 
the bloodshed. He said Yemeni Foreign Minister Muhammad Salim 
Basindwah has agreed to receive a delegation from the Arab 
League Secretariat headed by Major General Sa'id Bayraqdar, the 
assistant Arab League secretary general for military affairs. 
  Asked about reports that Yemeni Vice President 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid had requested Jordanian mediation to stop the fighting, 
al-Qadi said he has no information about this. He noted that 
Jordan has continued to call on the Yemeni leaders to begin 
negotiations and renounce force as a means to solve differences. 
He pointed to Jordan's role in signing the Pledge and Accord 
Document, which he described as the best option of the Yemeni 
people to solve differences and preserve a unified Yemen. 
  The Jordanian ambassador hoped the brothers in Yemen will 
come to their senses and stop battles as soon as possible so 
that differences can be solved through dialogue and 
understanding. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58963 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes090_j_94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-090 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister's Contacts Declared `Null and Void' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister's Contacts Declared `Null and Void' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0905133494 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1200 GMT 9 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0905133494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The House of Representatives held a session this 
morning under the speakership of brother Shaykh 'Abdallah 
Bin-Husayn al-Ahmar and in the presence of Foreign Minister 
Muhammad Salim Basindwah. The foreign minister explained to the 
House the actions taken by brother Engineer Haydar Abu-Bakr 
al-'Attas, the prime minister, on his medical and tourist trip, 
as well as his contacts and telephone conversations abroad with 
Arab and other officials. These contacts included the Arab 
League secretary general, the UN secretary general, certain 
Yemeni ambassadors, and our Arab League permanent 
representative. The foreign minister explained that al-'Attas 
exploited his position as prime minister by holding these 
contacts and asking for an Arab League peace-keeping force, thus 
allowing for the violation of our national sovereignty and 
national independence, when what is taking place in our country 
is no more than a war against those who have rebelled against 
constitutional legitimacy and democracy. 
  The foreign minister added that the advent of foreign troops 
to our country would undermine the sovereignty and independence 
of the country. He indicated that brother Haydar Abu-Bakr 
al-'Attas is exploiting his position as prime minister in a 
manner that does not serve the homeland as much as it serves a 
party faction. Moreover, our Arab League permanent 
representative has called for peacekeeping forces without 
obtaining the Council of Ministers' approval, but at the request 
of brother Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas, who has not received the 
approval of the Council of Ministers or the Foreign Ministry. 
Had our permanent representative believed in the homeland's 
interest, he would not have received his instructions from the 
prime minister, who is on a tourist trip abroad. 
  The brother foreign minister said the Arab League Council -- 
thanks to our national, candid, clear, and firm stand -- was 
satisfied with the adoption of a decision, whose most important 
point was the Arab League Council's reaffirmation of the 
statement it issued in March supporting Yemeni unity without 
reservation. 
  The House then discussed in detail the illegitimate foreign 
moves and activities of the brother prime minister, who is 
abroad on a medical trip. The House members approved the 
following House draft resolution: 
  In the name of God, the merciful, the compassionate. 
  Resolution by the House of Representatives: 
  During its session today, Monday, 29 Dhu al-Qi'dah 1414 
Hegira, corresponding to 9 May 1994, the House of 
Representatives discussed the moves and contacts made by brother 
Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas, the prime minister, and the political 
activities accompanying them in his official capacity as prime 
minister although he traveled for medical purposes and was not 
assigned with any official mission by the Presidential Council 
or the Council of Ministers. Since his talks, contacts, and 
statements deal with domestic Yemeni affairs and violate Article 
110 of the Constitution of the Republic of Yemen, which states 
that the role of the chairman of the Council of Ministers is 
confined to implementing the Council of Ministers' decisions and 
the state's general policy in a coordinated and unified manner; 
and in view of what is entailed by these contacts and moves in 
terms of negative repercussions that are detrimental to the 
sovereignty, independence, and supreme interests of Yemen, the 
House has decided the following: 
  1. His contacts and statements are totally null and void due 
to their violation of constitutional legitimacy in accordance 
with Article 110 of the Constitution of the Republic of Yemen. 
Moreover, any contacts or moves outside the framework of the 
constitutional institutions by any official or politician in the 
state are considered null and void and entail no legal 
commitment whatsoever. 
  2. The executive authority should implement the House 
resolution, communicate it to other states and international 
bodies and organizations, and adopt the necessary measures in 
accordance with the Constitution. May God grant us success. 
  Brother Dr. 'Abd-al-Salam Khalid Karman, minister of legal 
and House of Representatives affairs, attended today's session. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

