<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Outlines Contingency Plans for Evacuation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Outlines Contingency Plans for Evacuation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0805102594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0919 
GMT 8 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0805102594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Yuriy Tyssovskiy] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 8 May -- "We are making every effort to 
carry out, should the need arise, the rapid and organized 
evacuation from dangerous parts of Yemen of all Russian citizens 
working on contracts in that country," Viktor Posuvalyuk, 
director of the Africa and Near East Department of the Foreign 
Ministry of the Russian Federation told an ITAR-TASS 
correspondent in a telephone conversation. He said that 113 
people had already arrived by plane in Moscow from Djibouti, 
which borders on Yemen, after being brought there on the French 
warship, Jules Verne. 
  The Russian Foreign Ministry, says the Russian diplomat, is 
in constant contact with its colleagues from France. Should the 
situation worsen in Aden in the south of the country, we have 
obtained the agreement of Paris to bring out as many Russians as 
possible from there on a warship which is due to approach the 
port of Aden in the near future. Our consul general in the town 
has been given exhaustive instructions in this regard. As for 
the country's capital, Sanaa, we have plans to bring Russians 
out overland to the port of Al Hudaydah where our ship the 
Khudozhnik Kustodiyev is waiting. Although Sanaa airport is, 
according to our information, besieged and the situation there 
is unsafe, the Russian leadership has allocated two passenger 
planes which are ready to fly out there for our people if the 
situation is permits. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

